23.3.2 During the match, he/she is entitled to:

23.3.2.1 issue warnings to the teams;

23.3.2.2 sanction misconduct and delays;

23.3.2.3 decide on:

(a) serving faults and positional faults of the serving team, including net faults;

(b) faults in playing the ball;

(c) faults above the net and illegal contact of a player with the net, mainly (but not exclusively) on the attackers side;

(d) attack‑hit faults by the Libero and back‑row players;

(e) the completed attack hit by a player on a ball entirely above net height that comes from an overhand finger pass by the Libero in his/her front zone;

(f) the ball that completely crosses the lower space under the net;

(g) the completed block by a back‑row player or the attempted block by the Libero;

(h) the ball that crosses the net wholly or partly outside the crossing space to the opponents court or touches the antenna on his/her side of the court.

The second referee also checks during the match that the balls still comply with the regulations.

24.2.10 For FIVB, world and official competitions, the task listed in 24.2.5 is carried out by the reserve referee.

25 CHALLENGE REFEREE

25.1 LOCATION

25.2 DUTIES

24.3.1 At the beginning of each set, at the change of courts in the deciding set and whenever necessary, the second referee performs the checks.

24.3.2 During the match, he/she decides, whistles and signals:

24.3.2.1 penetration into the opponent’s court and the space under the net;

24.3.2.2 positional faults of the receiving team;

24.3.2.3 illegal contact of a player with the net, mainly (but not exclusively) on the blocker’s side, and with the antenna on his/her side of the court;

24.3.2.4 a completed block by back‑row players or an attempted block by the Libero, or an attack‑hit fault by back‑row players or by the Libero;

24.3.2.5 the ball contacting an external object;

24.3.2.6 the ball contacting the floor when the first referee is not in a position to see the contact;

24.3.2.7 the ball that crosses the vertical plane of the net wholly or partly outside the crossing space towards the opponent’s court or touches the antenna on his/her side of the …

… is determined by the FIVB court layout.

26.2 RESPONSIBILITIES

The reserve referee is required to:

26.2.1 wear an official refereeing uniform while performing his/her duties;

26.2.2 replace the second referee in case of his/her absence, inability to continue, or when the second referee becomes the first referee;

26.2.3 before the match and between sets, check the substitution paddles (if they are used);

26.2.4 check the operation of the team bench tablets before and between sets, if a problem arises;

26.2.5 assist the second referee in supervising the substitution zone;

26.2.6 help the second referee ensure that an expelled/disqualified team member leaves the team dressing room;

26.2.7 monitor the substitute players in the warm‑up area and on the bench;

26.2.8 immediately after the player introductions, bring four match balls to the second referee and, after the checking of the players, give one match ball to the second referee;

26.2.9 assist the first referee in supervising the work of the floor wipers.

27 SCORER

27.1 LOCATION

The scorer sits at the scorer’s table on the side of the court opposite the first referee and facing the court.

27.2 RESPONSIBILITIES

The scorer fills in the score sheet in accordance with the Rules, working in cooperation with the second referee.

The scorer works in cooperation with the referees.
He/she uses a buzzer or other audible device to report irregularities or to give signals to the referees within his/her responsibilities.

27.2.1 Before the match and each set, the scorer:

27.2.1.1 records the data of the match and the teams, including the names and numbers of the Liberos, in accordance with the applicable procedures, and obtains the signatures of the game captains and coaches;

27.2.1.2 records the starting line‑up of each team from the line‑up sheet (or checks the data transmitted electronically).

If he/she does not receive the line‑up sheets on time, he/she immediately informs the second referee.

27.2.2 During the match, the scorer:

27.2.2.1 records the points scored;

27.2.2.2 controls the order of service of each team and notifies the referees of any fault immediately after the service;

27.2.2.3 is authorized to confirm and announce substitution requests with the buzzer, control the number of players, record substitutions and time‑outs, and inform the second referee;

27.2.2.4 informs the referees of any request for a regular game interruption that is not correct;

27.2.2.5 informs the referees of the end of sets and of the scoring of the 8th point in the deciding set;

27.2.2.6 records warnings for misconduct, sanctions and illegal requests;

27.2.2.7 records all other events according to the instructions of the second referee, i.e. …

28.2.1.1 prepares the Libero control sheet;

28.2.1.2 prepares the reserve score sheet.

28.2.2 During the match, the assistant scorer:

28.2.2.1 records the details of Libero replacements / re‑designations;

28.2.2.2 notifies the referees of any Libero replacement fault using the buzzer;

28.2.2.3 operates the manual scoreboard at the scorer’s table;

28.2.2.4 checks that the scoreboards are consistent;

28.2.2.5 updates the reserve score sheet when necessary and hands it to the scorer.

28.2.3 At the end of the match, the assistant scorer:

28.2.3.1 signs the Libero control sheet and submits it for verification;

28.2.3.2 signs the score sheet.

For FIVB, world and official competitions where an electronic score sheet is used, the assistant scorer works together with the scorer to announce substitutions, direct the second referee to the team requesting an interruption, and identify Libero replacements.

29 LINE JUDGES

29.1 LOCATION

When only two line judges are used, they stand at the corners of the court on the right‑hand side of each referee, diagonally 1 to 2 m from the corner.

Each of them controls both the end line and the side line on his/her side …

… of the court.

When, in FIVB, world and official competitions, four line judges are used, they stand in the free zone 1 to 3 m from each corner of the court, on the imaginary extension of the line they control.

29.2 RESPONSIBILITIES

29.2.1 The line judges perform their duties using flags (40 x 40 cm) to signal:

29.2.1.1 whether the ball is "in" or "out" when the ball lands near their line(s);

29.2.1.2 touches of "out" balls by the receiving team;

29.2.1.3 the ball touching the antenna, and the served ball, the second and third team hit that cross the net outside the crossing space, etc.;

29.2.1.4 any player (other than the server) who leaves his/her position at the moment of the service hit;

29.2.1.5 foot faults by the server;

29.2.1.6 any contact with the top 80 cm of the antenna on their side of the court by a player while playing the ball or interfering with play;

29.2.1.7 the ball crossing the net outside the crossing space into the opponent’s court or touching the antenna on their side of the court.

29.2.2 At the request of the first referee, a line judge must repeat his/her signal.

SECTION 3 – DIAGRAMS

DIAGRAM 1a: COMPETITION / CONTROL AREA

Relevant rules: 1, 1.4.5, 4.2.1, 4.2.3.1, 15.4.2, 21.3.2.1, 21.3.3.1, 27.1, 28.1.

The diagram illustrates, for FIVB, world and official competitions:

- the competition/control area around the court;
- the position and approximate size of the team benches (about 3 x 3 m);
- the scorer’s table and the Technical Delegate’s (TD) table;
- the Libero replacement zone and the substitution zone;
- locations of LED panels and minimum safety distances (for example 20 cm, 15 cm, 5 cm, 1 m, 1.75 m, etc.);
- warm‑up areas (options 1 and 2) and the minimum width of the free zone (at least 3 m, recommended up to 6.5 m);
- overall dimensions of the free zone (minimum 24–31 m in length).

The values shown apply to FIVB, world and official competitions.

DIAGRAM 1b: THE PLAYING AREA

Relevant rules: 1, 1.4, 1.4.2, 1.4.3, 1.4.4, 1.4.5, 4.2.1, 4.2.3.1, 15.10.1, 19.3.1.4, 19.3.2.7, 23.1, 24.1, 27.1, 28.1.

The diagram shows:

- the dimensions of the court (18 x 9 m);
- the front and back zones and the service zones (at least 3 m, recommended 5 m behind each end line);
- the minimum width of the free zone (at least 3 m, recommended 6.5 m) on all sides of the court;
- the height and location of the referee’s stand (eye level about 1.75 m above the net);
- typical distances from court lines to barriers and advertising boards.

These values also apply to FIVB, world and official competitions.

DIAGRAM 2: THE PLAYING COURT (DETAILS)

Relevant rules: 1.1, 1.3, 1.3.3, 1.3.4, 1.4.1

The diagram specifies in detail how to measure:

- the front and back zones (3 m between the attack line and the centre line);
- the exact thickness and position of the boundary lines (side lines, end lines, centre line, attack lines – usually 5 cm wide);
- the dimensions of the service zones (at least 3 m, recommended 5 m behind each end line);
- the total dimensions of the court (18 m x 9 m) and the separation between front and back zones.

DIAGRAM 3: NET SET‑UP

Relevant rules: 2, 2.2, 2.3, 2.4, 2.5.1, 11.3.1, 11.3.2, 29.2.1.6

The diagram shows:

- the net length (9.50–10 m) and width (1 m);
- the height of the net: 2.43 m for men, 2.24 m for women, measured above the centre of the court (axis of the centre line), with the ends at 2.55 m including the antennae;
- the upper white band and side bands (about 5 cm wide) and the steel cable inside the top band;
- the position and height of the antennas (80 cm above the net, 10 mm wide, fixed on the outer edge of each side band).

DIAGRAM 4: POSITIONS OF THE PLAYERS

Relevant rules: 7.4, 7.4.3, 7.5, 23.3.2.3(a), 24.3.2.2

The diagram illustrates the positions of front‑row and back‑row players:

- C (centre) – middle player in the row;
- R (right) – right‑side player in the row;
- L (left) – left‑side player in the row.

It shows examples of correct positioning and faults (overlaps) between:

- a front‑row player and the corresponding back‑row player (Example A);
- players within the same row (Example B).

"Correct" indicates a legal position; "fault" indicates positional fault or overlap.
